3 Models v. date

lmDate arguments
1) (ycol) name of dependent variable in
2) (aDF) a data frame.
3) (maxrows) number of points in linear model (ndays = 42).

Optionally specify zero-weight for last zerwt dates and/or specified dates (zerdays).

  • For some dependent variables coronavirus.data.gov.uk marks last five as incomplete suggesting zerwt = 5.
  • For some dependent variables Xmas day and NY day are different suggesting zerdays = c(2020-12-25, 2021-01-01).

Output
Fit linear model to last maxrows dates, respecting any specified zero-weights. Model is quadratic in date, ln(y) ~ poly(date, 2), with optional day-of-week factor (wDay = TRUE).

  • Plot all data with loess(span = 0.1) smoother, omitting zero-weighted data from loess.
  • Plot linear model data points and fit line. If model includes day-of-week then, to clarify underlying trend, additionally plot fit line in which day-of-week always = Sunday.
  • Print text containing (differences calculated without any day-of-week factor):
    • latest fitted value, y1;
    • latest first difference, ln(y1) - ln(y2); expressed as doubling/halving time of y;
    • latest second difference, [ln(y1) - ln(y2)] - [ln(y2) - ln(y3)]; expressed as doubling/halving time of first difference.
  • Plot linear model residuals v. date.
  • Print linear model descriptive statistics. (NB Model is intended as descriptive, not predictive. P-values and hypothesis test statistics are not easily interpretable.)

3.1 Tests

Linear model over 9 weeks.

with(lmDate(Tests, UKDF, 63, wDay = TRUE),{ 
print(lplot + logy)
print(xyplot + logy )
cat(tailstr, "\n\n")
print(resplot)
print(anova(lm))
print(summary(lm))   })

IndCh <- function(ycol, aDF, maxrows = nrow(aDF) - 7, xcol = date){
require(ggplot2, quietly = TRUE)
  # get x,y columns as char
  xcol  <- deparse(substitute(xcol))  
  ycol  <- deparse(substitute(ycol)) 
  # subset data frame, get needed cols
  aDF <- na.omit(aDF[, c(match(ycol, names(aDF)), match(xcol,names(aDF)))])
  aDF <- aDF[order(aDF[,2], decreasing = FALSE), ] # ensure increasing x order
  aDF$ratio <- c(rep(NA,7), exp(diff(log(aDF[,1]), 7))) # calc ratio to week ago
  aDF <- tail(aDF, maxrows)
  ggplot(aDF, aes(x = .data[[xcol]] ,y = ratio)) + 
    labs(subtitle = paste0("Ratio " , ycol, "/week ago with 7 day rolling mean")) +
    scale_x_date(date_breaks = "1 week", date_labels = "%d/%m") +
    geom_hline(yintercept = 1) +
    geom_point() +
    geom_line(aes(y = zoo::rollmean(ratio, 7, NA, align = "center")), colour = "red") #+
   # geom_line(aes(y = zoo::rollmean(ratio, 14, NA, align = "right")), colour = "blue") +
  #  geom_line(aes(y = zoo::rollmean(ratio, 21, NA, align = "right")), colour = "black") 
}
IndCh(PubCases, UKDF, 63) #+ logy

IndCh2 <- function(ycol, aDF, maxrows = nrow(aDF) - 7, lag = 1, xcol = date){
require(ggplot2, quietly = TRUE)
  # get x,y columns as char
  xcol  <- deparse(substitute(xcol))  
  ycol  <- deparse(substitute(ycol)) 
  # subset data frame, get needed cols
  aDF <- na.omit(aDF[, c(match(ycol, names(aDF)), match(xcol,names(aDF)))])
  aDF <- aDF[order(aDF[,2], decreasing = FALSE), ] # ensure increasing x order
  aDF$rmean <- zoo::rollmean(aDF[,1], 7, NA, align = "right") # rolling mean
  aDF$ratio <- c(rep(NA,lag), exp(diff(log(aDF$rmean), lag = lag))) # calc diff
  aDF <- tail(aDF, maxrows)
  ggplot(aDF, aes(x = .data[[xcol]] ,y = ratio)) + 
    labs(subtitle = paste0("Ratio 7-day arithmetic mav(" , ycol, ")/", lag, " days ago with 7 day geometric mav of ratio")) +
    scale_x_date(date_breaks = "1 week", date_labels = "%d/%m") +
    geom_hline(yintercept = 1) +
    geom_point()  +
    geom_line(aes(y = exp(zoo::rollmean(log(ratio), 7, NA, align = "center"))), colour = "red") #+
    #geom_line(aes(y = zoo::rollmean(ratio, 14, NA, align = "right")), colour = "blue") +
    #geom_line(aes(y = zoo::rollmean(ratio, 21, NA, align = "right")), colour = "black") 
}
IndCh2(PubCases, UKDF, 63) #+ logy
